---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import GtmNoscript from '../components/GtmNoscript.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import { SITE_DESCRIPTION, SITE_TITLE } from '../consts';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<BaseHead title={SITE_TITLE} description={SITE_DESCRIPTION} />
	</head>
	<body>
		<GtmNoscript />
		<Header />
		<main>
			<h1>hungovercoders</h1>
			<p>
				I wanted a single place on the internet that was mine. Source-controlled, cheap to run,
				honest about how it works. The kind of tech blog you'd write if you didn't have to impress
				anyone — just help a fellow hungovercoder get something working before the next round.
			</p>
			<p>This is it.</p>
			<p>
				The posts are walkthroughs of things I actually built — data pipelines, cloud infrastructure,
				APIs, DevOps tooling, and these days a lot of working alongside AI agents. Not theoretical.
				Not sanitised. Some written on a Friday night, most polished on a Sunday morning with the dog
				asleep on the sofa. The code ran on my laptop first.
			</p>
			<p>
				The worldview, if you want it in one sentence: <strong>small, cheap, and yours beats big,
				fancy, and rented.</strong> If one slightly hungover person can't deploy it on a Tuesday —
				or a Saturday morning with a head on them — it's too complicated.
			</p>
			<p>
				AI is on the team now. Claude Code (and friends) does the typing; I do the judgement. The
				blog is what comes out the other side — what I built, what I rewrote, what I'd do differently.
				The opinion's still mine.
			</p>
			<p>
				<a href="/blog">Read the blog</a> or <a href="/about">find out who's behind it</a>.
				Read on, fellow hungovercoder.
			</p>
		</main>
		<Footer />
	</body>
</html>
